<dl id="sa0571t"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="sa" href="#sa0571t">SA (VI.A) </a>: <a href="../../FF/fnbs/ssaall.htm#sa0571t"> 571(t)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> aaaa b cinquain, quatrain, with cccc b pentastich,</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">A favourite form is the Rub&aacute;&apos;&iacute; or <mark>quatrain</mark>, made familiar to English ears by Mr Fitzgerald&apos;s masterly adaptation of OMar-i-Khayy&aacute;m &hellip; The Mukhammas, <mark>cinquains or pentastichs</mark> (<cite>Night</cite> cmlxiv.), represents a stanza of two distichs and a hemistich in monorhyme &hellip; e.g., <mark><i>aaaab</i> + <i>ccccb</i></mark>. <small> Richard Burton, &ldquo;Terminal Essay&rdquo; in <a name="RB01" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#RB01"><cite title="source">1000 Nights and 1 Night</cite></a> (Denver, 1919) x.266</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
